Project Report¶

Project Objectives¶

Our project objective is to predict the trend and the exact stock price of a company from January 1, 2019 to March 31, 2019 to two groups of people, which are potential stakeholders and current stakeholders. Our potential stakeholders are investors and speculators. Whereas our current stakeholders are corporate management, shareholders and employees.

In order to do so, we chose three companies we interested within different industries, which are Apple, Disney, and Ford. We found the best model for our main target company and tested the best model to the other two companies under different industries to check if it is universally applicable. In the end, we generated stock price trend in graphs that are easily readable to our stakeholders and exact stock price of a day. Besides, to better predict the price, we introduced natural language processing and sentiment analysis based on news so that our stakeholders can used to conduct more insightful analysis.

Instruction of Stage¶

Part 1: Using stock historical data

  • Step1: Data process and preparation
    • Combining data set. Combine Disney stock historical data with market indexes, aligned with date.
    • Visualization. Draw a line plot of historical data to have an intuition and basic image of the trend and fluctuation.
    • Calculating derived variables to improve prediction.
  • Step 2: Model test
    • Experimented neural network, ARIMA, LSTM and SVM models to predict the trend and exact price in future.
  • Step 3: Applied best model to other companies to check whether it is universally applicable
    • As the SVM model hit the best prediction result, we choose it as our prediction model and applied this model to other two companies, Ford and Apple, to check whether it is also universally applicable in other industries.

Part 2: Sentiment analysis on social media and news

  • Step 4: Scraping text from tweet and Reuters news
    • Scraping data from Twitter. We applied a Twitter Developer App and took advantage of Twitter API to scrape Tweets. More than 2000 pieces of Tweet are collected.
    • Scraping data from Reuters. We chose Reuters as our target news portal and scraped more than 200 news articles on Apple company. These articles dates from August, 2018 to the most recent days.
  • Step 5: Text cleaning and processing
    • Removing punctuation.
    • Tokenization.
    • Customizing stopword list and removing stopwords.
    • Stemming and lemmatization.
    • Testing quality of text cleaning and repeat above steps.
  • Step 6: Word frequency count and visualization
    • Top 20 words frequency count
    • Word frequency line chart and word cloud
  • Step 7: Sentiment analysis
    • Date extracting. Using regular expression to extract publishing date and convert them into timestamp format.
    • Sentiment analysis. Using nltk package to do sentiment analysis
  • Step 8: Combining sentiment analysis with stock price to check its influence.
    • Calculate correlation.
    • Visualization. Draw heatmap and line&bar plot to its correlation.

Data Description and Source¶

Our data mainly concluded into two parts:

  • The first part is historical stock data from Yahoo Finance, which dates from January 1, 2014 to March 31, 2019. Also, we included some market index to reflect the market prosperity. Based on these data sets, we calculated some variables to improve our analysis, including moving average, exponential average and RSI.

  • The second part is text data we scraped from social media, Twitter (using Twitter API), and news portal, Reuters. The details will be shown in codes below. The scraped result and text data we got included more than 2000 Tweets and more than 200 news. We stored the tweets into .csv file, includes user name, text, and time stamp. And news content is stored in .txt file, with a .csv file to store the title and time stamp of each news.

The details of each variables are shown below:

Variables from Yahoo Finance:¶

Date: The trading date

Open: Opening price on that day

High: The highest price reached on that day

Low: The lowest price reached on that day

Close: Closing price on that day

Volume: The number of shares traded on that day

Market Index: Index based on Date

S&P 500: an American stock market index based on the market capitalizations of 500 large companies

DJI: a stock market index that indicates the value of 30 large, publicly owned companies

NASDAQ: a stock market index of the common stocks and similar securities listed on the NASDAQ stock market

Variables from Our Calculation:¶

Moving Average(5 days, 10 days & 20 days): Three calculation fields based on Date. It is a calculation to analyze data points by creating a series of average of 5 days, 10 days & 20 days of the full data set.

Moving average 5 days

Moving average 10 days

Moving average 20 days

Exponential moving average: A calculation fields based on Date. It is a weighted moving average that gives weighting to recent price data.

Relative Strength Index (RSI): A calculation fields based on Date. It is an indicator that measures the magnitude of recent price changes to evaluate overbought or oversold conditions. (14 days)

Variables from Twitter:¶

User: the users screen name

Text: the text or content of this tweet

Time: the timestamp of this tweet or when the tweet is published

Variables from Reuters:¶

ID: the ID of news article, act as an index to find its content .txt file

Title: the title of news article

Time: the timestamp of news article, or when the article is published

Data Process¶

Historical data

  • Combine data sets. Combine target company data with market indexes, aligned with date.
  • Transform: moving average, exponential average and RSI
  • Transform: Close-1 to Close-20. Add last 20 days close price to the variables by using a for loop and df.shift().
  • Scale: using preprocessing.StandardScaler() or MinMaxScaler() to scale the dataset except dependent variable--Close
  • Split dataset into training and test.
  • Visualization: Draw a line plot to show its trend and fluctuation.

Sentiment analysis based on news title

After reading the csv file from the local, the data frame has some cleaning tasks need to be done as following:

  • Firstly, we deleted the first column which only shows the indexes of the news.
  • To get the exact date from the original data, e.g. March 22, 2019 / 6:11 AM / a month ago. We used the re.match with the pattern '(\w+\s\d+[,]\s\d{4})' to get the format: March 22,2019. Then replace the white space and comma with - and transform the whole column using pd.to_datetime(news.Date, format='%B-%d-%Y'). Finally, we got 2019-3-22.
  • For news which are duplicate in the data frame, we deleted them through command news.drop_duplicates(keep = False, inplace = True). For dates which have more than one news, we grouped them by date and calculate the average sentiment score.
  • We labeled the news title 1 as positive when its sentiment score is larger than 0.2, similarly, -1 as negative when sentiment score is smaller than -0.2. Otherwise, we labeled it 0 as neutral.
  • To find out the impact of news on the stock price at that day, we checked the date when both news breaks and the stock market opens.

Text processing based on news content

The scraped news contents from Reuters are in text format and saved in a folder. To further process the data we conducted the following procedures:

  • We used a loop to read all the text files in one folder into a list of lists of string. Each string represented content of a text file in the folder.
  • We used list(itertools.chain.from_iterable()) to iterate the list of lists of string to a list of strings. Then, we looped through the list to convert the list of strings to lowercase strings and ready for our cleaning phase.
  • After we printed out the string, we realized there are many unnecessary punctuations and existing URLs included, such as \x93, \'b\' and URL. We used replace() and re.sub() to remove all unnecessary punctuations.
  • To break the string into words, we tokenized the string using word_tokenize() and filtered the stopwords using stopwords.words('english').
  • To format the words into the most popular format so that we can count the frequency of them in later analysis, we stemmed and lemmatized the words using PorterStemmer() and WordNetLemmatizer()
  • We count the top 20 words frequency to test to quality of data cleaning. However, there are not only many unnecessary punctuations exist again, but also unnecessary words that have high frequency exist. The unnecessary punctuations are caused by the tokenization of the URLs, and the unnecessary words are due to the news content itself. For example, there is (reuters) signature exists for each Reuters news, which are unnecessary and caused high frequency. Another example is stephen and nellis. Stephen Nellis is the reporters of Reuters that specifically reports Apple news, but this name is unnecessary for our analysis. Therefore, we went back and forth many times from removing punctuations to updating and filtering stopwords to exclude these unnecessary and meaningless punctuations and words until the data has been well cleaned.

Data Analysis¶

ARIMA

Autoregressive Integrated Moving Average Model (ARIMA) is a model usually used in time series forecasting. As stock prices may have some relationship with its past data, ARIMA should be a model fit our problem. We took 5-year historical data as training data to fit our model. During the adjustment of the model, we figured out there is very weak seasonality exists in this data set so we removed seasonality feature from this model. However, this might not be the case as we test the model in the other two companies in the future. After testing the model with 90-day testing data, the best model we got for ARIMA is ARIMA(0,1,0) with mse of 2.81.

Neural Network

Neural network model is typically used in machine learning for its advantage on handling a large number of variables and no need to make any assumption of relationships among variables. The best neural network structure we finally chose is one has three hidden layers with 512, 256, 128 nodes on each layer. And the activation function we chose for input layer and hidden layer is ReLU. But the activation function for output layer is linear to get the exact prediction of the stock price.

Long short-term memory (LSTM)

LSTM are used in sequence prediction problems because LSTM can store past information that is important and forget the unimportant information. We prepared the data and fit the 5-year training data with LSTM model, and tested the model with 90-day testing data to get the test MSE of 1.91 and Loss of 0.0054. Finally, we plot the actual and predicted trend from January 1, 2019 to today to see the performance.

SVC

To predict whether the stock price is up or down in one day, all three accuracies of SVC model with different kernels reach more than 95%. Based on our prediction, the return of the disney stock in first three months in 2019 is nearly 20%, not considering the trade costs, while the stock price itself fluctuates between -5% and 5%.

SVR

From the figure we can see that the predicted results fit the real close price very well. The model captures nearly all the trends of market change, and can also get a return of 20%. By comparing the two lines in the figure, whenever the stock is going to be down, the model will not buy in the stock and the strategy line is flatten. Thus, the ROI keeps increasing when the stock is going to be up and remains steady when it will be down in three months.

We also try this model on other two companies, Apple and Ford, to see whether the model is universally applicable. SVR model also forecasts the general trends of two stocks accurately, but the returns of Apple and Ford vary greatly. Apple has been up more than 30% in the first 3 month, while the overall return undergoes an increase trend with fluctuation and finally reaches less than 5%. The return of Ford keeps rising if we calculate the ROI by cumulatively product each days return.

Sentiment analysis

We find that there is no significant correlation between the News sentiment score and the volatility of the stock price. During 2019-11 to 2019-04, Apple stock has risen a lot, while there is much more negative news than positive news during this period.

Text Processing based on News Content

The words frequency figure shows the visualized frequency of the top 10 most common words in Reuters news content from August 2018 to the latest, which are apple, iphone, company, inc, qualcomm, service, year, sale, chip and percent. The word cloud gives us more information about the popular words in the news, like China, Amazon, App, TV and etc.

Conclusion of Findings and Application¶

There are many factors could have influences on the stock price and make it difficult to predict. Some market indexes may reflect the overall trends, but individual stocks vary dramatically. Through technical methods and historical data we can find some rules in the past. Based on our models results, some may have certain prediction power. Comparing the models we used in the project, SVM has an overall better performance than 3 other models in predicting the stock price, but it also has limitations as we list below. We recommend that investor should not trust those funds have so-called high returns in a short period. Secondly, a short-term investment strategy may avoid many risks of uncertainty, but you may also have less returns. For example, if we had chosen to keep the apple stock for 3 month, we would have had a return of 30%.

For breaking news, there is no significant correlation between the sentiment score and the volatility of the stock, which is somehow contrary to the common sense. Sometimes, it is caused by the market panic and the investors should not be emotional.

Limitations:

  • For SVM model itself, if we increase the parameter C in SVM.SVC, penalty parameter C of the error term, the accuracy will increase but also require a longer runtime.
  • In the model, we use the past 20 days close price and one days open price to predict the close price. We can make prediction only if we know the open price for that day after the market opens and cannot use it for a long-term investment.
  • To calculate the return, we make the assumption that we can make investment decision as soon as we know the open price and apply it to our model. And also, there is no trading cost when we buy in the stock and sell it at the end of the day.

Moving Average¶

As Adam Hayes puts, a moving average (MA) is a widely used indicator in technical analysis that helps smooth out price action by filtering out the noise from random short-term price fluctuations. It is a trend-following, or lagging, indicator because it is based on past prices.

So, we introduce moving average to our model, to filter out noise in daily prices, which is a common phenomenon for stock maket.

Expoentional Moving Average¶

According to Inverstopedia, exponential moving average (EMA) is a type of moving average (MA) that places a greater weight and significance on the most recent data points. The exponential moving average is also referred to as the exponentially weighted moving average.

So, we also inluded EMA in our model, to attach more importance on recent prices.

In [11]:
def EMA(values, window):
    """to calculate exponential mobing average"""
    weights = np.exp(np.linspace(-1., 0., window))
    weights /= weights.sum()
    a =  np.convolve(values, weights, mode='full')[:len(values)]
    a[:window] = a[window]
    return a

#Calculating RSI
def RSI(series, period = 14):
    u = series * 0
    d = u.copy()
    u[series > 0] = series[series > 0]
    d[series < 0] = -series[series < 0]
    u[u.index[period-1]] = np.mean( u[:period] ) #first value is sum of avg gains
    u = u.drop(u.index[:(period-1)])
    d[d.index[period-1]] = np.mean( d[:period] ) #first value is sum of avg losses
    d = d.drop(d.index[:(period-1)])
    #
    rs = pd.DataFrame.ewm(u, com=period-1, adjust=False).mean() / pd.DataFrame.ewm(d, com=period-1, adjust=False).mean()
    rsi = 100 - 100 / (1 + rs)
    return rsi

#build neural network structure
model = Sequential()
model.add(Dense(units = 1024, activation = 'relu', input_dim = X.shape[1]))
model.add(Dense(units = 512,activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(units = 256, activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(units = 128,  activation = 'relu'))
model.add(Dense(units = 1, activation = 'linear'))
model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', loss = 'mean_squared_error', metrics = ['accuracy'])
model.fit(X_train, y_train, epochs = 100)

LSTM Model¶

LSTM are used in sequence prediction problems because LSTM can store past information that is important and forget the unimportant information

In [4]:
#load packages for LSTM
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler
from keras.models import Sequential
from keras.layers import Dense, Dropout, LSTM

Using TensorFlow backend.

    y_train.append(scaled_data[i,0])

model.compile(loss='mean_squared_error', optimizer='adam')
model.fit(x_train, y_train, epochs=1, batch_size=1, verbose=2)

In [22]:
#2014.1.1-2018.12.31 has 1258 recordings, used as training data
train=1258
L=len(dfsvc)
total_predict_data=L-train
predict_result=np.zeros(61)

#drop the DV
df_CB_X=dfsvc.drop(['Value'],axis=1)
correct = 0
train_original=train
while train<L:
    #use the historical 1258 rows data 
    Data_train=df_CB_X[train-train_original:train]
    value_train = dfsvc['Value'][train-train_original:train]
    Data_predict=df_CB_X[train:train+1]
    value_real = dfsvc['Value'][train:train+1]

    #classifier = svm.SVC(C=100, kernel='poly',gamma='scale') 
    classifier = svm.SVC(C=1000,kernel='linear',gamma='scale')
    #classifier = svm.SVC(C=1000,kernel='rbf',gamma='scale')
    classifier.fit(Data_train,value_train)
    value_predict=classifier.predict(Data_predict)
    predict_result[train-1258]=value_predict
    if(value_real[0]==int(value_predict)):
        correct=correct+1
    train = train+1
correct=correct*100/total_predict_data
print("Correct=%.2f%%"%correct)

Correct=100.00%

Both model svm.SVC(C=100, kernel='poly',gamma='scale') and svm.SVC(C=1000,kernel='linear',gamma='scale') reach 100% accuracy, other models also reach accuracy of more than 95%.

In [34]:
svc_result = pd.DataFrame(predict_result,index=dfsvm.index[1258:])
svc_result.columns = ['position']
svc_result['real']=value[1258:]
svc_result['open'] = dfsvm['Open'][1258:]
svc_result['close'] = dfsvm['Close'][1258:]
svc_result['PL'] = np.where(svc_result['position'] == 1, (svc_result['close'] - svc_result['open']) / svc_result['open'], 0)
svc_result['strategy'] = (svc_result['PL'] + 1).cumprod()
svc_result['price pct_change'] = (svc_result['close'].pct_change() + 1).cumprod()
svc_result[['strategy', 'price pct_change']].dropna().plot(figsize=(8,4),title='ROI (one day)')
Out[34]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x20736744f98>

If we buy in the stock as soon as we know the open price and the model tells us that the stock will go up today, and sell it at the end of the day. We will get returns about 20% during 4 months, without considering trading costs.

In [40]:
#ROI-SVR
#assuming no trading costs
svr_result['open'] = dfsvm['Open'][1258:]
svr_result['position'] = np.where(svr_result['predicted close'] > svr_result['open'], 1, 0)
svr_result['PL'] = np.where(svr_result['position'] == 1, (svr_result['close'] - svr_result['open']) / svr_result['open'], 0)
svr_result['strategy'] = (svr_result['PL'] + 1).cumprod()
svr_result['price pct_change'] = (svr_result['close'].pct_change() + 1).cumprod()
svr_result[['strategy', 'price pct_change']].dropna().plot(figsize=(8,4),title='Disney ROI (one day)')
Out[40]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x20737c17198>

The strategy avoids all the risks when Disney Stock price drops and also reach the return of 20% during 4 months.

Scrape Tweets¶

In [1]:
#change working directory
import os

In [2]:
import tweepy
import csv
import json
In [ ]:
# credential data is hidden
with open('twitter_credentials.json') as cred_data:
    info = json.load(cred_data)
    consumer_key = info['CONSUMER_KEY']
    consumer_secret = info['CONSUMER_SECRET']
    access_token  = info['ACCESS_KEY']
    access_token_secret  = info['ACCESS_SECRET']

class PrintListener(tweepy.StreamListener):
    def on_data(self, data):
        # Decode the JSON data
        tweet = json.loads(data)

        user_name=str(tweet['user']['screen_name'])
        text=str(tweet['text'].encode('ascii', 'ignore'))
        time=str(tweet['created_at'])
        content=[user_name,text,time]
        print(content)
        writer.writerow(content)
        #print('@%s: %s,%s' % (tweet['user']['screen_name'], tweet['text'].encode('ascii', 'ignore'),tweet['created_at']))

    def on_error(self, status):
        print(status)


if __name__ == '__main__':
    """this model should be stopped by manual, otherwise, it will run continuously"""
   
    # to extract to .csv file
    with open('Apple_tweets.csv', 'w', encoding='utf8') as f:
        writer = csv.writer(f)
        writer.writerow(['user', 'text', 'time'])
        
        listener = PrintListener()

        # Show system message
        print('I will now print Tweets containing "Apple"! ==>')

        # Authenticate
        auth = tweepy.OAuthHandler(consumer_key, consumer_secret)
        auth.set_access_token(access_token, access_token_secret)

        # Connect the stream to our listener
        stream = tweepy.Stream(auth, listener)
        stream.filter(track=['Apple'])

We scraped more than 2000 tweets contains feature word 'Apple', and save the result into a .csv file for following steps.

In [ ]:
# to get all news models
soup = BeautifulSoup(driver.page_source, 'lxml')
paragraph=soup.find_all('h3')
len(paragraph)
In [ ]:
# to get all the news url link, for further scrape their content
link=[]
pat='<a href=\".+\"'
for item in paragraph:
    m = re.search(pat,str(item))
    href=m.group()
    link.append(href[9:-1])
len(link)
In [ ]:
import os
os.chdir("D:\python\\UMDpythonGroup\\apple")
In [ ]:
apple_news=dict()
In [ ]:
# to get content of each news
for i in range(len(link)):
    item=link[i]
    time.sleep(random.randrange(5,15))
    # the domain url
    domain='https://www.reuters.com/'
    req = Request(domain+item, headers={'User-Agent': 'Mozilla/5.0'})
    webpage = urlopen(req).read()
    soup = BeautifulSoup(webpage, 'html.parser')

    # details to store in .csv
    title=str(soup.find_all('h1'))[36:-6]
    time_stamp=str(soup.find_all('div')[50])[32:-6]
    apple_news[i]=[title,time_stamp]

    # content of news
    paragraph=soup.find_all('p')[1:-2]
    content=[]
    for p in paragraph:
        content.append(str(p)[3:-4])
    # to export to .txt file
    with open(str(i)+'.txt','w') as f:
        for p in paragraph:
            f.write("%s\n" % str(p)[3:-4])
In [ ]:
# the total list of news, containing ID, title, time
with open('apple_news.csv', 'w') as csv_file:
    writer = csv.writer(csv_file)
    for key, value in apple_news.items():
        writer.writerow([key, value[0],value[1]])

import re
pat = '(\w+\s\d+[,]\s\d{4})'

#Extract date in the second column
for i in range(len(news['Date'])):
    m = re.match(pat,news['Date'].iloc[i])
    news['Date'].iloc[i]=m.group()
pat1='\s'
news['Date']=news['Date'].str.replace(pat1,'-')
news['Date']=news['Date'].str.replace(',','')

    results.append(pol_score)

precision industry co ltd, pegatron corp, wistron corp and compal electronics inc - became embroiled in the dispute between apple and qualcomm last year. \'b\'in the supply chain for electronics, it is the contract manufacturers who buy qualcomm\\x92s chips and pay royalties when they build phones, and they are in turn reimbursed by companies like apple. qualcomm sued the group last year, alleging they had stopped paying royalties related to apple products, and apple joined their defense. \'b\'the contract manufacturers have since filed claims of their own against qualcomm, alleging the san diego company\\x92s practice of charging money for chips but then also asking for a cut of the adjusted selling price of a mobile phone as a patent royalty payment constitutes an their antitrust claims. \'b\'ted boutrous, a high-profile partner at gibson, dunn &amp; crutcher llp who is representing the contract manufacturers, said statements from qualcomm executives suggesting (reporting by vibhuti sharma in bengaluru; editing by arun koyyur)\'b\'new york (reuters breakingviews) - apple and qualcomm have faced up to their mutual need. the $940 billion smartphone maker and $85 billion mobile-chip firm on tuesday ended a two-year fight over royalties with a licensing agreement and a cash payment to qualcomm. apple can\\x92t risk being stuck with second-rate semiconductors in its devices, and qualcomm has huge revenue at stake. at first blush, both sides benefit from the truce. \'b\'their lawyers have been kept busy since 2017 by the argument over how qualcomm charges for chips that connect smartphones to data networks. apple accused qualcomm of withholding parts from suppliers unless they agreed to pay high royalties, something the iphone maker said was anti-competitive. qualcomm said apple had put pressure on suppliers not to pay. the numbers were pretty big, even for such huge companies: apple was seeking as much as $27 billion in damages, while its supplier-cum-adversary wanted up to $15 billion. \'b\'the nature of the truce is hazy. neither side is saying how big apple\\x92s payment is, or what future royalties will be. qualcomm did point out in a presentation to investors, however, that it expects an incremental $2 per share of earnings; details on exactly how and when that flows through are nonexistent, but with 1.2 billion shares outstanding, that probably implies a hefty payment. history suggests apple, meanwhile, will get sweeter terms than it had before the dispute. about a decade ago, then-dominant phone maker nokia and qualcomm settled a similar dispute with nokia getting a discount. \'b\'investors seem to believe there are no losers. apple\\x92s shares rose slightly, adding around $1 billion to its market capitalization, reflecting that it will now have access to 5g chips from the dominant supplier. that\\x92s better than the risk of delays in future iphones, or worse, inferior handsets. qualcomm\\x92s market value jumped by $15 billion, or more than a fifth, as investors penciled in large, high-margin royalty payments down the road. both sides can just about claim to have come out on and an online gaming arcade. \'b\'with appearances by oprah winfrey and steven spielberg, the world\\x92s second-most valuable technology company lifted the curtain on a television and movie company\\x92s long-expected plunge into the streaming video war is years behind leaders netflix inc and amazon.com inc. apple left out key details such as pricing, making it difficult to judge how its service will stack up against competitors.  \'b\'\\x93while apple may introduce a bigger roster of original content than amazon and netflix during their respective launches, the streaming \\xa0market has arguably already reached a level of saturation and consumer fatigue in the united states,\\x94 said colin gillis, an analyst at chatham road partners. \'b\'the programming will come through a gregorio\'b\'feb 7 (reuters) - apple inc has moved its modem chip engineering effort into its in-house hardware technology group from its supply chain unit, two people familiar with the move told reuters, a sign the tech company is looking to develop a key component of its iphones after years of buying it from outside suppliers. \'b\'modems are an indispensable part of phones and other mobile devices, connecting them to wireless data networks. apple once used qualcomm inc chips exclusively but began phasing in intel corp chips in 2016 and dropped qualcomm from iphones released last year. \'b\'johny srouji, apple\\x92s senior vice president of hardware technologies, took over the company\\x92s modem design efforts in january, the sources said. the organizational move has not been previously reported. \'b\'srouji joined apple in 2008 to lead chip design, including the custom a-series processors that power iphones and ipads and a special bluetooth chip that helps those devices pair with its airpods wireless headphones and other apple accessories. \'b\'the modem efforts had previously been led by rub\\xe9n caballero, who reports to dan riccio, the executive responsible for ipad, iphone and mac engineering, much of which involves integrating parts from the company\\x92s vast electronics supply chain. \'b\'apple declined to comment. technology publication the information previously reported that apple was working to develop its own modem chip. \'b\'the cupertino, california-based company has posted job listings for modem engineers in san diego, a hub for wireless design talent because of qualcomm\\x92s longtime presence there and a place where apple has said it plans to build up its workforce. \'b\'apple\\x92s effort to make its own modem chips could take years, and it is impossible to know when, or in what devices, such chips might appear. \'b\'\\x93when you\\x92re apple, everything has to be good,\\x94 said linley gwennap, president of chip industry research firm the linley group. \\x93there\\x92s no room for some substandard component in that phone.\\x94 \'b\'apple\\x92s investment in modem chips comes as carriers and other phone makers are rolling out devices for the next generation of faster wireless networks known as 5g. \'b\'rival handset makers samsung electronics co ltd and huawei technologies co ltd already make their own modems. \'b\'making its own modem chips would likely cost apple hundreds of millions of dollars or more per year in development costs, analysts said, but could save it money eventually. \'b\'modem chips are a major part of the cost of apple devices, worth $15 to $20 each and likely costing apple $3 billion to $4 billion for the 200 million or so iphones it makes a year, said bernstein analyst stacy rasgon. \'b\'apple may also benefit by combining its modem chips with its processor chips, as samsung, huawei and most other phone makers do. that saves space and battery life, two important considerations if apple introduces augmented reality features into future products. \'b\'class="attribution_content">reporting by jan  wolfe; editing by paul simao and tom brown\'b\'(reuters) - apple inc and its allies on monday will kick off a jury trial against chip supplier longtime business partners to quit paying some royalties and is seeking up to $15 billion. \'b\'filed by apple in early 2017, the lawsuit in federal court revolves around the modem chips that connect devices like the iphone or apple watch to wireless data networks. qualcomm has spent the past two years mounting a pressure campaign of smaller legal skirmishes against apple, seeking - and in some technology path for blockbuster products by buying chips without having to pay what it calls a \\x93tax\\x94 on its innovations in the form of patent licensing fees to qualcomm that take a cut of the selling price of its devices.  \'b\'for qualcomm, the trial, along with similar allegations from u.s. regulators in a january court hearing, will determine the fate of its unique blend of selling chips and licensing more than 130,000 patents.  \'b\'licensing generates most of qualcomm profits. the model propelled qualcomm from a small contract research and development shop when founded in 1985 to a global chip powerhouse important enough to u.s. national security that president donald trump personally intervened to prevent a hostile takeover of the company last year. \'b\'\\x93this is the day of reckoning that qualcomm has been very fortunate to avoid for many years,\\x94 said gaston kroub, a patent attorney with kroub, silbersher &amp; kolmykov who is not involved in the case. \\x93in device makers to sign a license to its patents before it will supply chips, which it views as a commonsense measure to ensure it does not do business with companies violating its patents. but apple and other device makers around the world have called the \\x93no license, no chips\\x94 policy a form of \\x93double dipping\\x94 - that is, charging for the same intellectual property once during licensing discussions, and then again in the price of the chips where the patents are embodied. \'b\'apple and allies are asking for an end to that practice and a refund of about $9 billion - an amount that could be tripled if a jury finds in apple\\x92s favor for antitrust allegations - for contract factories such as hon hai precision industry co ltd\\x92s foxconn, who paid the royalties and were reimbursed by apple. apple alleges the practices kept rivals like intel corp out of the market for years. \'b\'\\x93even very big companies like intel have felt at a disadvantage,\\x94 said michael salzman, an antitrust attorney with hughes hubbard &amp; reed not involved in the case. \'b\'qualcomm will argue that it had been working successfully with contract factories for years before apple introduced its iphone. but apple used its heft in the industry to get those factories to break their longstanding contracts with qualcomm, depriving it of at least $7 billion in royalties it was due, the chip supplier alleges.  \'b\'the chip supplier will also argue that its licensing practices have been consistent for decades and only came under fire when apple, known in the electronics coming online this year. \'b\'\\x93i don\\x92t think (a qualcomm victory) would be great for apple, but if it\\x92s about money, they\\x92ve got plenty of money,\\x94 said stacy rasgon, an equity (reporting by stephen nellis in san francisco; editing by lisa shumaker)\'b\'(reuters) - mobile phone chip supplier qualcomm inc on friday won a legal victory against iphone maker apple inc, with a jury in federal court in san diego finding that apple owes qualcomm about $31 million for infringing three of its patents. \'b\'qualcomm last year sued apple alleging it had violated patents related to helping mobile phones get better battery life. during an eight-day trial, qualcomm asked the jury to award it unpaid patent royalties of up to $1.41 per iphone that violated the patents. \'b\'the $31 million penalty is small change for apple, the second most valuable u.s. company after microsoft corp, with a market value of $866 billion and annual revenue totaling hundreds of billions of dollars. but the setting of a per-phone royalty rate for qualcomm\\x92s technology gives the chip supplier a fresh line of attack in its two-year old legal battle with apple. \'b\'the biggest case, filed by apple in early 2017, begins in april. apple has sought to dismantle what it calls qualcomm\\x92s illegal business model of both licensing patents and selling chips to phone makers. qualcomm has accused apple of using its technology without paying. \'b\'\\x93the technologies invented by qualcomm and others are what made it possible for apple to enter the market and become so successful so quickly,\\x94 don rosenberg, qualcomm\\x92s general counsel, said in a statement. \\x93we are gratified that courts all over the world are rejecting apple\\x92s strategy of refusing to pay for the use of our ip.\\x94 \'b\'in a statement, apple said it was disappointed with the outcome. \'b\'\\x93qualcomm\\x92s ongoing campaign of patent infringement claims is nothing more than an attempt to cautioned it was not clear how much of that was coming from the license deal versus the supply agreement. \'b\'analysts were also unsure whether  apple\\x92s a onetime payment under the deal makes many of the same claims of anticompetitive behavior remains unresolved, with a decision expected at any time. \'b\'a jury of six men and three women was in the process of hearing opening apple inc plans to cut the price of some of its flagship iphones for only the second time in the device\\x92s 12-year history, pegging its retail value to past prices in local currencies outside the united states instead of the rising u.s. dollar.  \'b\'the move is an attempt to stem weak sales of the iphone, particularly in overseas markets such as china, where a 10 percent rise in the u.s. dollar over the past year or so has made apple\\x92s products - which already compete at the top end of the market - much pricier than rivals.  \'b\'apple chief executive tim cook disclosed the plan on tuesday after the company reported the first-ever dip in iphone sales during the key holiday shopping period. the company has only once before cut iphone prices, shortly after it debuted in 2007. \'b\'apple did not say in which countries it would adjust iphone prices. resellers in china already began cutting iphone prices earlier this month after apple lowered its sales forecast for the quarter ended in december. \'b\'the company priced its new iphone xs, which was released in september, at $999, the same price in u.s. dollars as its predecessor, 2017\\x92s iphone x.  \'b\'that worked for u.s. consumers, but in countries such as china and turkey the local currency had fallen so much against the surging u.s. dollar, it made the phone significantly pricier than its predecessor a year before. apple had essentially asked the consumer to bear the cost of the strengthening dollar. \'b\'on tuesday, cook said apple will adjust foreign prices in some markets by resetting them at or close to what they were one year before in local currencies. effectively that means apple will absorb the cost of the strengthening dollar. \'b\'\\x93we\\x92ve decided to go back to (iphone prices) more commensurate with what our local prices were a year ago, in hopes of helping the sales in those areas,\\x94 cook told reuters in an interview.    \'b\'in the company\\x92s quarterly earnings call on tuesday, cook also highlighted the impact of foreign exchange problems in turkey, where he said the local lira had depreciated by 33 percent against the dollar and apple\\x92s sales were down by $700 million from the previous year. in november, apple also cited currency pressure on its prices in brazil, india and russia.  \'b\'apple has not said when or how often it might reset its prices because of foreign currency changes. \'b\'chief financial officer luca maestri said the price adjustments may not extend to its services business, which includes apple music and the app store. \'b\'while that unit beat analyst expectations with $10.8 billion in sales in the quarter ended in december, growth has slowed compared to previous years. \'b\'maestri said slower growth was partly \'b\'class="attribution_content">reporting by noel randewich; editing by phil berlowitz and richard chang\'b\'washington (reuters) - when iphone users want to edit blemishes out of their selfies, identify stars and constellations or simply join the latest video game craze, they turn to apple inc\\x92s app store, where any software application they buy also includes a 30 percent cut for apple.  \'b\'that commission is a key issue in a closely watched antitrust case that will reach the u.s. supreme court on monday. the nine justices will hear arguments in apple\\x92s bid to escape damages in a lawsuit accusing it of breaking federal antitrust laws by monopolizing the market for iphone apps and causing consumers to pay more than they should. \'b\'the justices will ultimately decide a broader question: can consumers even sue for damages in an antitrust case like this one?  \'b\'apple, which is appealing a lower court decision that revived the proposed consumer class-action lawsuit, says no, citing a decades-old supreme court precedent. the cupertino, california-based technology company said that siding with the iphone users who filed the lawsuit would threaten the burgeoning field of e-commerce, which generates hundreds of billions of dollars annually in u.s. retail sales.  \'b\'the plaintiffs, as well as antitrust watchdog groups, said that if the justices close courthouse doors to those who buy consumer products, monopolistic conduct could expand unchecked.  \'b\'\\x93a lot of tech platforms will start making the argument that consumers don\\x92t have standing to bring antitrust suits against us,\\x94 said sandeep vaheesan, legal director for the open markets institute, a washington-based antitrust advocacy group.  \'b\'\\x93uber could say, we\\x92re just providing communication services to ride-sharing drivers,\\x94 vaheesan said, referring to the popular ride-sharing company. \\x93if there\\x92s an antitrust issue, the drivers can bring a claim but passengers do not have standing.\\x94  \'b\'the iphone users accused apple of violating federal antitrust law by monopolizing the sale of paid apps, leading to inflated prices compared to if apps were available from other sources. \'b\'though developers set the prices of their apps, apple collects the payments from iphone users, keeping a 30 percent commission on each purchase. one area of dispute in the case is whether app developers recoup the cost of that commission by passing it on to consumers. developers earned more than $26 billion in 2017, a 30 percent increase over 2016, according to apple. \'b\'the company sought to have the antitrust claims dismissed, saying the plaintiffs lacked the required legal standing to bring the lawsuit.  \'b\'apple has seized upon a 1977 supreme court ruling that limited damages for anti-competitive conduct to those directly overcharged instead of indirect victims who paid an overcharge passed on by others. part of the concern, the court said in that case, was to free judges from having to make complex calculations of damages.  \'b\'apple said it is acting only as the agent for app developers who sell the apps to consumers through the app store.  \'b\'the company said allowing the lawsuit to proceed would be dangerous for the e-commerce industry, which increasingly relies on agent-based sales models. apple cited companies like ticket site stubhub, amazon\\x92s marketplace and ebay.  \'b\'lawsuits against companies like these would multiply \\x93and lead to the quagmire this court sought to avoid,\\x94 apple told the justices in a legal brief.  \'b\'e-commerce reached $452 billion in u.s. retail sales in 2017, according to u.s. government estimates. \'b\'apple is supported by president donald trump\\x92s administration. the plaintiffs are backed by the attorneys general of 30 states including california, texas, florida and new york. \'b\'the u.s. chamber of commerce business group, backing apple, said in a brief to the justices, \\x93the increased risk and cost of litigation will chill innovation, discourage commerce, and hurt developers, retailers and consumers alike.\\x94 \'b\'the plaintiffs and some anti-monopoly groups disagree. they said that app developers would be unlikely to sue because they would not want to bite the hand that feeds them, leaving no one to challenge anti-competitive conduct.  \'b\'developers \\x93cannot risk the possibility of apple removing them from the app store if they bring suit,\\x94 the american antitrust institute advocacy group said in a brief. \'b\'apple is \\x93trying to make it harder for injured parties to assert their rights under federal antitrust law,\\x94 said mark rifkin, an attorney for the plaintiffs. \'b\'the claims against apple date to 2011 when several iphone buyers including lead plaintiff robert pepper of chicago filed a class action lawsuit against apple in federal court in oakland, california. a judge initially threw out the suit, ruling that the consumers were not direct purchasers because the higher fees they paid were passed on to them by the developers. \'b\'the san francisco-based 9th u.s. editing by will dunham\'b\'san francisco (reuters) - software pirates have hijacked technology designed by apple inc to distribute hacked versions of spotify, angry birds, pokemon go, minecraft and other popular apps on iphones, reuters has found. \'b\'illicit software distributors such as tutuapp, panda helper, appvalley and tweakbox have found ways to use digital certificates to get access to a program apple introduced to let corporations distribute business apps to their employees  without going through apple\\x92s tightly controlled app store. \'b\'using so-called enterprise developer certificates, these pirate operations are providing modified versions of popular apps to consumers, enabling them to stream music without ads and to circumvent fees and rules in games, depriving apple and legitimate app makers of revenue. \'b\'by doing so, the pirate app distributors are violating the rules of apple\\x92s developer programs, which only allow apps to be distributed to the general public through the app store. downloading modified versions violates the terms of service of almost all major apps. \'b\'tutuapp, panda helper, appvalley and tweakbox did not respond to multiple requests for comment.  \'b\'apple has no way of tracking the real-time distribution of these certificates, or the spread of improperly modified apps on its phones, but it can cancel the certificates if it finds misuse. \'b\'\\x93developers that abuse our enterprise certificates are in violation of the apple developer enterprise program agreement and will have their certificates terminated, and if appropriate, they will be removed from our developer program completely,\\x94 an apple spokesperson told reuters. \\x93we are continuously evaluating the cases of misuse and are prepared to take immediate action.\\x94 \'b\'after reuters initially contacted apple for comment last week, some of the pirates were banned from the system, but within days they were using different certificates and were operational again.  \'b\'\\x93there\\x92s nothing stopping these companies from doing this again from another team, another developer account,\\x94 said amine hambaba, head of security at software firm shape security. \'b\'apple confirmed a media report on wednesday that it would require two-factor authentication - using a code sent to a phone as well as a password - to log into all developer accounts by the end of this month, which could help prevent certificate misuse.  \'b\'major app makers spotify technology sa, rovio entertainment oyj and niantic inc have begun to fight back.  \'b\'spotify declined to comment on the matter of modified apps, but the streaming music provider did say earlier this month that its new terms of service would crack down on users who are \\x93creating or distributing tools designed to block advertisements\\x94 on its service.  \'b\'rovio, the maker of angry birds mobile games, said it actively works with partners to address infringement \\x93for the benefit of both our player community and rovio as a business.\\x94 \'b\'niantic, which makes pokemon go, said players who use pirated apps that enable cheating on its game are regularly banned for violating its terms of service. microsoft corp, which owns the creative building game minecraft, declined to comment.  \'b\'it is unclear how much revenue the pirate distributors are siphoning away from apple and legitimate app makers.  \'b\'tutuapp offers a free version of minecraft, which costs $6.99 in apple\\x92s app store. appvalley offers a version of spotify\\x92s free streaming music service with the advertisements stripped away. \'b\'the distributors make money by charging $13 or more per year for subscriptions to what they calls \\x93vip\\x94 versions of their services, which they say are more stable than the free versions. it is impossible to know how many users buy such subscriptions, but the pirate distributors combined have more than 600,000 followers on twitter.  \'b\'security researchers have long warned about the misuse of enterprise developer certificates, which act as digital keys that tell an iphone a piece of software downloaded from the internet can be trusted and opened. they are the centerpiece of apple\\x92s program for corporate apps and enable consumers to install apps onto iphones without apple\\x92s knowledge.  \'b\'apple last month briefly banned facebook inc and alphabet inc from using enterprise certificates after they used them to distribute data-gathering apps to consumers. \'b\'the distributors of pirated apps seen by reuters are using certificates obtained in the name of legitimate businesses, although it is unclear how. several pirates have impersonated a subsidiary of china mobile ltd. china mobile did not respond to requests for comment.  \'b\'tech news website techcrunch earlier this week reported that certificate abuse also enabled the distribution of apps for pornography and gambling, both of which are banned from the app store. \'b\'since the app store debuted in 2008, apple has sought to portray the iphone as safer than rival android devices because phone for qualcomm\\x92s patents. \'b\'the san diego jury valued just three of qualcomm\\x92s patents in the company\\x92s portfolio at $1.41, a figure that the chip supplier believes bolsters its contention that its licensing practices are fair. \'b\'\\x93the three patents found to be infringed in this case represent just a small fraction of qualcomm\\x92s valuable portfolio of tens of thousands of patents,\\x94 rosenberg said in a statement. \'b\'gaston kroub, a patent lawyer in new york not involved in the case, said the verdict was clearly a win for qualcomm. but it does not say christopher cushing\'b\'(reuters) - apple inc said thursday that it will resume selling older iphone models in its stores in germany, where they were banned last year due to a patent infringement ruling. \'b\'the iphones will be sold in germany only with chips from qualcomm inc, instead of a mix of chips from qualcomm and intel corp. qualcomm is in a global legal battle against cupertino-based apple over patent licensing, and the german case was part of the chip supplier\\x92s efforts to rack up smaller wins ahead of a major lawsuit with apple that goes to trial in april in san diego. qualcomm last year also won a ban on sales of some iphones in china. \'b\'apple said it had \\x93no choice\\x94 but to stop using some chips from intel corp in iphones headed to germany in order to comply with the patent infringement ruling. \'b\'qualcomm, the world\\x92s biggest supplier of mobile chips, sued apple in germany alleging that some older iphone 7 and iphone 8 models violated qualcomm patents around so-called envelope tracking, a feature that helps mobile phones save battery power while sending and receiving wireless signals. the alleged patent violation stemmed not from intel chips but yet another apple supplier - qorvo inc - whose chip was only present in older phones with intel modems. \'b\'the court sided with qualcomm and banned sales of some iphone models that used intel modem chips, leading apple to pull the devices from its 15 retail stories in germany and its online store in the country. \'b\'the ban was a victory in qualcomm\\x92s legal conflict with apple. \'b\'the iphone maker has alleged that qualcomm engaged in illegal patent licensing practices to protect a monopoly on so-called modem chips, which connect mobile phones to wireless data networks. qualcomm has in turn alleged that apple has infringed its patents. a major case between the two goes to trial in the united states in april. \'b\'apple began phasing in intel\\x92s modem chips in 2016 after years of using chips exclusively from qualcomm. in last year\\x92s iphone models, apple dropped qualcomm\\x92s chips completely in favor of intel\\x92s. \'b\'but qualcomm has \'b\'newer iphones with intel chips remain on sale in germany. \'b\'\\x93intel\\x92s modem products are not involved in this lawsuit and are not subject to this or any other injunction,\\x94 steven rodgers, intel\\x92s general counsel, said in a statement. \'b\'class="attribution_content">reporting by stephen nellis; editing by christopher cushing and david gregorio\'b\'san francisco (reuters) - apple inc and qualcomm inc on tuesday settled an acrimonious two-year legal dispute. shortly afterward, intel corp said it will exit the smartphone modem chip business. \'b\'the entire drama played out as the mobile phone industry prepares to shift to a technology called 5g.  \'b\'echoing complaints from the u.s. federal trade commission, apple had alleged that qualcomm used its patent licensing business to keep a monopoly on modem chips that connect devices like the iphone to wireless data networks. qualcomm insisted that apple was using its valuable technology without proper payment, and apple later dropped qualcomm\\x92s chips in favor of those from intel. \'b\'in the end, apple and qualcomm ceased all litigation, with apple signing a six-year licensing deal with qualcomm and also agreeing to buy qualcomm chips. hours later, intel said it was getting out of the modem chip business. [nl3n21y466] \'b\'5g is a new network technology for wireless communications that could be up to 100 times faster than current 4g networks. the networks are coming on line in the united states, china, south korea and other places this year, but probably will not be widespread until 2020. modem chips connect devices like phones to these networks.  \'b\'prior to tuesday, five companies had disclosed 5g modem chips or plans to make them: qualcomm, intel, mediatek inc, huawei technologies co ltd and samsung electronics co ltd. samsung and huawei, however, only make chips for their own mobile phones.   \'b\'some of apple\\x92s rivals in the smartphone market - notably samsung - plan to release 5g devices this year, which could put pressure on apple to match the feature. many carriers that are investing heavily to build 5g networks are also likely to put their marketing efforts behind 5g phones.  \'b\'it would require an extraordinary effort from both companies. new modems take months of testing to ensure phones will work on carrier networks. under traditional time lines, apple would have needed to start testing a 5g iphone last year, but its supplier intel did not have a chip ready. \'b\'apple was slow to 4g too and did not pay a price. samsung and others released 4g phones in 2011 as the networks were rolling out. apple waited until 2012, when 4g networks become widely accessible. many analysts believe apple is making the same bet with 5g. \'b\'apple\\x92s only current modem supplier, intel, said that it would not have a 5g chip ready until 2020, which could have pushed apple\\x92s launch of a 5g iphone into 2021 - a long enough delay that it could hurt sales. qualcomm, on the other hand, is preparing to ship its second generation 5g chip and can meet apple\\x92s needs with its current products.  \'b\'not necessarily. while apple and qualcomm signed a supply agreement, apple is working on developing its own modems and disclosed in court earlier this year that it has held talks with mediatek and samsung around modems. \'b\'why did intel share rise after it exited the modem business? \'b\'intel chief executive bob swan has told investors in the past that modem chips are not likely to fetch the same high margins as its cpu chips. intel has plenty of other ways to make money from 5g, like selling cpus to makers of base stations and so-called programmable chips to makers of networking gear. \'b\'(the story corrects \\x93with\\x94 to \\x93without\\x94 in paragraph 3) \'b\'class="attribution_content">reporting by stephen nellis in san francisco; editing by greg mithcell and lisa shumaker\'b\'(reuters) - We can see from here, there are many unnecessary punctuation exsists due to the character type of the text file and the remaining links from scraping. Also, there are high frequency meaningless words like 'Reuters' and the authors name who published the news. These can't be filtered from dictionary of stopwords, so we have to mannually clean them. The following steps are the text cleaning.













In [10]:



    


#remove all unnecessary punctuation
strapple = re.sub('[-$.<()>]', '', strapple)
strapple = re.sub(";'b\'", '', strapple)
strapple=strapple.replace("\\",'')
strapple=strapple.replace('x93','')
strapple=strapple.replace('x92','')
strapple=strapple.replace('x94','')
strapple=strapple.replace('x96','')
strapple=strapple.replace("b\'",'')
strapple=strapple.replace("''",'')
strapple=strapple.replace("'",'')
strapple=strapple.replace(',','')
strapple=strapple.replace(';','')
strapple=strapple.replace('class="attribution_content"','')
strapple=strapple.replace('href="','')
strapple=strapple.replace('://','')
strapple=strapple.replace('/','')



    













In [ ]:



    


# Word tokenization
applewords=word_tokenize(strapple)
# Filter stop words from tokenized words
applewords=[appleword for appleword in applewords if appleword not in stopwords.words('english')]
# Stopwords for apple ONLY
applestopword=['reuters','said','symbol','stephen','nellis','financestocksoverview','reporting','span','id','would','also']
# Filter stop words from tokenized words
applewords=[appleword for appleword in applewords if appleword not in applestopword]
print(applewords)



    















We repeated removing unnecessary punctuation and word filtering stopwords many times by manually removing more punctuation and adding more stopwords to the dictionary in order to make sure there is no meaningless words with high frequency.













In [ ]:



    


# Stemming
ps = PorterStemmer()
print([ps.stem(appleword) for appleword in applewords])



    













In [ ]:



    


# Lemmatizataion
lmtzr = WordNetLemmatizer()
applewords = [lmtzr.lemmatize(appleword) for appleword in applewords]
print(applewords)



    















The existing URLs caused a lot of problem so that there are unnecessary punctuation appear again.

#remove''
for index, item in enumerate(applewords):
    if (item =="''"):
        applewords.remove(applewords[index])
